PRE-REQUISITE: Set a company to subscription_status=ACTIVE with trial_ends_at in the past via SQL:

UPDATE "Company" SET subscription_status='ACTIVE', trial_ends_at='2020-01-01T00:00:00Z' WHERE id='<id>';

Run expire-now — locked must be 0. The WHERE clause filters subscription_status=TRIAL only, so ACTIVE companies are never touched.

PRE-REQUISITE: Set a company to subscription_status=TRIAL with trial_ends_at=NULL:

UPDATE "Company" SET subscription_status='TRIAL', trial_ends_at=NULL WHERE id='<id>';

Run expire-now — locked must be 0. Postgres evaluates NULL < now() as NULL (not true), so { lt: now } naturally excludes null rows.

PRE-REQUISITE: Set a company to subscription_status=TRIAL with a future trial_ends_at:

UPDATE "Company" SET subscription_status='TRIAL', trial_ends_at='2099-01-01T00:00:00Z' WHERE id='<id>';

Run expire-now — locked must be 0. trial_ends_at is in the future so { lt: now } is false.
